Survival analysis - Squid Game style - Episode 2 - Dalgona candy

Installing required packages

# to install the other packages, run the codes below
# install.packages("survival")
# install.packages("survminer")

Loading packages

library("survival")
library("survminer")
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Loading required package: ggpubr

Loading dataset

Each column represents:

  1. players = player identifier
  2. shapes = four dalgona shapes, circle, triangle, star and umbrella
  3. dead_alive = dead or alive at the end of the game
  4. time_to_end_game = time each player takes to end the game
# load player dataset
players_full <- read.delim("player_stats_ep2_v2.txt")
head(players_full)
# convert time_to_end_game and dead_alive to numeric
players_full$time_to_end_game <- as.numeric(players_full$time_to_end_game)
players_full$dead_alive <- as.numeric(players_full$dead_alive)

Plotting survival curves

# assigning time and status 
time = players_full$time_to_end_game
status = players_full$dead_alive

model <- survfit(Surv(time, status) ~ shapes, data = players_full)

# plotting the survvial curve
ggsurv <- ggsurvplot(model, risk.table = TRUE, color="shapes", palette = c("#ff6f00", "#c71000", "#008ea0", "#8a4198"), data=players_full, pval = TRUE, 
                     ggtheme = theme_bw())
                     
ggsurv

Interpretation of results

Here we can see that players who chose the star shape are more likely to win the dalgona candy game and survive.

The star shape is one of the easiest shapes to carve as it has the shortest lines.

Players who chose the umbrella shape had the lowest probability of surviving the game since the umbrella shape is the most difficult.

We employed the log-rank test to compare the distribution of time until the game ends across all four groups. P < 0.0001 means that there is a significant difference between the survival curves.
